        public EmpiricalDistribution(double[] pdf,

                             RandomEngine randomGenerator)
        This is the inherited constructor from cern.jet.random.Empirical. It will not give meaningful K-S test D^ values (let alone p-values unless the input probability density function data happens to satisfy 0 F(x) 1.

        To use other types of empirical data the overloaded constructor uk.ac.qmul.sbcs.evolution.convergence.util.stats.EmpiricalDistribution.EmpiricalDistribution(double[] pdf, int interpolationType, RandomEngine randomGenerator, ProbabilityDensityFunction originalPDF) should be used.

        pdf - - real-valued probability density function (assumed to be binned uniformly from 0:1)
        interpolationType -
        randomGenerator -

    • Method Detail

      • cdf

        public double cdf(double val)

        This method implemented according to jsc.distributions.Distribution, although a similar method occurs in cern.jet.random.Empirical
        In that case 

        Empirical.cdf(int i)
        simply returns the ith bin from the CDF.

        This is clearly not compatible with jsc.distributions.Distribution.cdf(double val) which would seem to expect a value of the CDF on (0:1] for a given value.
        This implies that the PDF may have been similarly transformed to a unit distribution. If so, a similar transformation should apply here, and the call to cdf(double val) would need to be mapped to the correct CDF bin.
        On the other hand, if the untransformed distribution is used then some way of retained the bins is needed.

        It might be worth overloading the constructor to accept a ProbabilityDensityFunction so that the ProbabilityDensityFunction.binIntervals can be retained.

        Parameters:
        val - - The proportion of observations on [0:1], not a real-valued variate from the observed data.
        See Also:
        jsc.distributions.Distribution#cdf(double)
